      <attr>
        <attrlabl>rd_design</attrlabl>
        <attrdef>Design characteristic of the road</attrdef>
        <attrdefs>ARNOLD Data Dictionary</attrdefs>
        <attrdomv>
          <edom>
            <edomv>SC = Single Carriageway</edomv>
            <edomvd>A roadway with one, two or more lanes arranged within a single course with no central reservation or median to separate opposing flows of traffic.</edomvd>
            <edomvds>ARNOLD Data Dictionary</edomvds>
          </edom>
          <edom>
            <edomv>HF = Highway Facility</edomv>
            <edomvd>A road segment that leads or traverse a rest area, welcome area, or a weigh station, etc.</edomvd>
            <edomvds>ARNOLD Data Dictionary</edomvds>
          </edom>
          <edom>
            <edomv>DC = Dual Carriageway</edomv>
            <edomvd>A physically divided roadway that necessitates two or more sets of line work to adequately represent the roadway geometry. According to the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA), divided facilities should be represented as dual carriageway if: The median width is four ft or greater and continues for 500 ft or the median type is a positive barrier</edomvd>
            <edomvds>ARNOLD Data Dictionary</edomvds>
          </edom>
          <edom>
            <edomv>RA = Grade- Separated Ramp</edomv>
            <edomvd>Connecting roadways that permit traffic flow from one mainline route to another without crossing any other traffic stream (found at controlled access interchanges, e.g. access ramps on an interstate highway)</edomvd>
            <edomvds>ARNOLD Data Dictionary</edomvds>
          </edom>
          <edom>
            <edomv>CS = Connector Segment</edomv>
            <edomvd>Minor road segments that permit traffic flow from one route to another without crossing any other traffic. These segments can be signed for official use only for government, law enforcement or emergency use only.</edomvd>
            <edomvds>ARNOLD Data Dictionary</edomvds>
          </edom>
          <edom>
            <edomv>FR = Frontage Road</edomv>
            <edomvd>A frontage road (also known as an access road, service road, parallel road, etc.) is a local road running parallel to a higher-speed, limited-access road. A frontage road is often used to provide access to private driveways, shops, houses, industries or farms. Where parallel high-speed roads are provided as part of a major highway, these are also known as local-express lanes.</edomvd>
            <edomvds>ARNOLD Data Dictionary</edomvds>
          </edom>
          <edom>
            <edomv>RG = At grade Ramp</edomv>
            <edomvd>Connecting roadways that permit traffic flow from one uncontrolled access route to another without crossing an other traffic stream, e.g. “turkey foot” intersection</edomvd>
            <edomvds>ARNOLD Data Dictionary</edomvds>
          </edom>
          <edom>
            <edomv>TC = Traffic Circle</edomv>
            <edomvd>The intersection of two or more roadways in an uncontrolled at-grade interchange, intended to keep traffic moving through the intersection.</edomvd>
            <edomvds>ARNOLD Data Dictionary</edomvds>
          </edom>
          <edom>
            <edomv>LR = Levee Road</edomv>
            <edomvd>The road segment is unpaved and traverses a flood control structure</edomvd>
            <edomvds>ARNOLD Data Dictionary</edomvds>
          </edom>
        </attrdomv>
